properties.name: Babylon Theater Obama Party
properties.description: Posted by Tracy_the_astonishing     Rosa-Luxemburg-Platz 10178 Berlin Erik, Vigo, and I went to the Democratic election night event at the Babylon. This is the first election my son Vigo, who is almost 8, is going to remember when he grows up and I wanted to show him that democracy is a celebration and I wanted to to be sure that he could say, "I was there," when he grows up. Because of the time zone difference, we didn\'t get the first results until after 11 PM. We got Vigo into a sleeping bag in a cozy spot at the back of the theater and drank beer and took turns walking around the party. I met people there from Camaroun, Germany, Greece, and France. Of course most of the crowd was American, but everyone was very emotional. Barak\'s acceptance speech came on at about 6 AM our time and we woke Vigo up to hear it. After that, we climbed on our bikes and rode home to get Vigo off to school by 8!

properties.name: Family Gathering, Dancing in the streets
properties.description: Posted by Deisnor   635 NE Going Street, Portland, ORWe wanted to believe he could win but the mood was anxious as we awaited the results. There has been so much injustice and so much defeated optimism in the past years. We sat in front of the projector in the living room streaming msnbc live and in a matter of seconds saw electoral votes soar from 207 to 284. We didn\'t cheer- we were too shocked and maybe skeptical. The kids were in sleeping bags on the floor, all of the adults sat around and wept and then finally were swept away into the cheering and awe. We danced outside and the kids banged pots and pans. When we woke up this morning, we wanted to buy an American flag. We reclaimed something we never had- a deep feeling of patriotism and icons of the US have evolved from historic artifact to beacon of hope and work. We will all go to Obama HQ this morning and keep the community engagement moving. We will all work hard in the next years to make America the just and inventive nation we can all build.

properties.description: Posted by Tracy_the_astonishingI was at work, where I make sliced cheese that we sell to places like McDonalds. It was agony having to wait for each break to find out who won! Finally, I came down to see McCain\'s defeat speech. It was awesome! I wanted to shout out, but had to bite my tongue a little since this is a notorious Republican stronghold and I didn\'t want to gloat and get people angry at me. But it\'s nice knowing that finally the Republicans are eating the crow we\'ve been eating for the last eight+ years.

properties.description: Posted by Raelity portland, orI was at home with the flu when I heard Obama was to be our next president -- our first presidential president in a long time. My wife and kids were off at an election night party. I curled up at home around my Apple cinema display and plugged in to the community -- indeed the world -- via Twitter, CNN video, Google (Election) Maps, IM, and many more. I was surprised at just how excited I was -- in retrospect I guess I was just coming to grips with the fact that life was about to get better.
